The theory of relativity, developed by Albert Einstein, is a way of understanding how the laws of physics apply to objects that are moving at high speeds or in different gravitational fields. There are two parts to the theory: the special theory of relativity and the general theory of relativity.

The special theory of relativity says that the laws of physics are the same for all observers, no matter how fast they are moving or in what direction. It also says that the speed of light is always the same, no matter how fast an observer is moving or how far away the light source is. This means that

Endless horizon glows,
Sunrise paints the waves anew,
Ocean breathes in peace.
